Working with the mean

A group of 99 friends each have some sweets. They work out that the mean number of sweets they have is 66. Then 44 friends leave with an unknown number (xx) of sweets. The remaining 55 friends work out that the mean number of sweets they have left is 2,42,4.

How many sweets (xx) were taken away from the group?

Answer:

The number of sweets taken away is .

numeric
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 3 / 3 points left]
Use the formula for the mean to figure out the total number of sweets in the original group.
STEP: Find the total number of sweets at the beginning
[−1 point ⇒ 2 / 3 points left]

We know that the mean number of sweets the group originally had was 66. Since there are 99 people in the group we can find the total number of sweets in the beginning using the formula for the mean:

meannumber ofsweets (before)=(number ofsweets (before))group size=mean×group size=(6)×(9)=54mean=(number ofsweets (before))group sizenumber ofsweets (before)=mean×group size=(6)×(9)=54
STEP: Find the total number of sweets after the 4 people leave
[−1 point ⇒ 1 / 3 points left]

We are then told that 44 people leave. After that, the mean number of sweets left is 2,42,4. We can then find out how many sweets remain.

meannumber ofsweets (after)=(number ofsweets (after))group size=mean×group size=(2,4)×(5)=12mean=(number ofsweets (after))group sizenumber ofsweets (after)=mean×group size=(2,4)×(5)=12
STEP: Find the number of sweets taken from the group
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 3 points left]

Now we can work out the number of sweets which were taken from the original group.

number ofsweets removed=items before−items after=(54)−(12)=42number ofsweets removed=items before−items after=(54)−(12)=42

The correct answer is 4242 sweets.

    where:

    • nn is the number of values in the data set
    • rr is the rank (position) of the pthpth percentile in the data set

    pn=25=11p=25n=11
    STEP: Substitute into the formula and evaluate the answer

The range

Consider the set of raw data:

{7;8;9;6;7;6;11;5;9;11;5}{7;8;9;6;7;6;11;5;9;11;5}

What is the range of the data set?

Answer: Range:
numeric
STEP: <no title>
[−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

The most useful step towards solving any data problem is to sort the data first.

{5;5;6;6;7;7;8;9;9;11;11}{5;5;6;6;7;7;8;9;9;11;11}

The range of a set of data is the difference between the highest and lowest values in the set. In order to find the range, we should do the following:

  • Organise the data
  • Identify the lowest value
  • Identify the highest value and subtract them
RangeRangeRange=Highest value - lowest value=11−5=6Range=Highest value - lowest valueRange=11−5Range=6

Therefore, the range of the data set is 6.
